It’s widely agreed that 1972 was a wake-up call for Pierre Trudeau, shocking him out of complacency and showing that charisma was not enough. The electoral near-death experience strengthened him for the long run. #cdnpoli 12/n

In 1972 the NDP was bursting with ideas and energy (though not always harmoniously). It targeted foreign ownership, business tax breaks, and corporate greed. Leader David Lewis coined his famous term “corporate welfare bums.” #cdnpoli 6/n

Meanwhile, the 1972 Conservatives were led by a decent, amiable leader, Robert Stanfield, who nevertheless failed to excite Canadians, and who oversaw a divided party with a sometimes bitter ex-leader (John Diefenbaker) still in the ranks. #cdnpoli 4/n

The 1972 Liberal slogan, ‘The Land is Strong,’ has gone down as the most vacuous in Canadian political history. The campaign was framed as a ‘conversation with Canadians’ - with little thought that Trudeau would need to actually persuade them to vote Liberal. #cdnpoli 3/n
